## Theorem: translated_imo_2002_p2a

Theorem: translated_imo_2002_p2a
Given: b c = segment b c
Given: o = midpoint o b c
Given: a = on_circle a o b
Given: d = on_circle d o b, on_bline d a b
Given: e = on_bline e o a, on_circle e o b
Given: f = on_bline f o a, on_circle f o b
Given: j = on_pline j o a d, on_line j a c
Prove: prove that ∠ece = ∠jej

Goal: eqangle e c e j e j e f

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Use coordinates with O as the origin and BC on the x-axis; then the circle conditions force A, D, E, F to lie on the same circle, and the perpendicular-line condition for J gives a simple linear equation that lets us compare the angles at E and J via slopes.",
  "plan": [
    "Place B and C symmetrically on the x-axis and write O as the midpoint at the origin.",
    "Use the circle hypotheses to compute the coordinates of A, D, E, and F.",
    "Use the bisector condition on D to determine its x-coordinate, then use the line/bisector conditions to obtain equations for E and J.",
    "Compute the relevant slopes of the rays defining ∠ECE and ∠JEJ, and show they are equal.",
    "Conclude that the two angles are equal."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may choose coordinates B = (-1,0), C = (1,0), and O = (0,0).",
      "reasoning": "Since O is the midpoint of BC, we can place the segment BC symmetrically on the x-axis with O at the origin. This is a standard coordinate normalization and preserves all incidences, lengths, and angle relations.",
      "facts_used": [
        "coordinate normalization for Euclidean geometry",
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point A has coordinates A = (u,v) for some real numbers u,v satisfying u^2+v^2 = 1, and v ≠ 0.",
      "reasoning": "A lies on the circle centered at O through B, so OA = OB = 1. Since O is the origin and B = (-1,0), the circle is x^2+y^2=1, hence A=(u,v) with u^2+v^2=1. The point A is not on the x-axis in the nondegenerate configuration relevant to the theorem, so v≠0.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle",
        "distance formula"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point D is the reflection of A across the x-axis, so D = (u,-v).",
      "reasoning": "The condition on_bline d a b means D lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment AB, so DA = DB. Together with D on the circle centered at O through B, D also satisfies x^2+y^2=1. The two points on that circle equidistant from A and B are symmetric with respect to the x-axis in this coordinate setup, giving D=(u,-v).",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector",
        "distance formula",
        "symmetry of the circle x^2+y^2=1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point E has coordinates E = (u,-v) or E = (u,v) depending on the chosen intersection, and in either case E lies on the same circle x^2+y^2=1.",
      "reasoning": "From on_bline e o a, E lies on the perpendicular bisector of OA, so EO = EA. From on_circle e o b, E also satisfies EO = OB = 1. Hence E is on the circle x^2+y^2=1 and on the perpendicular bisector of OA. Solving these equations gives the intersection point(s) explicitly; the one used in the configuration is determined uniquely by the diagram, and it lies on the same unit circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector",
        "definition of circle",
        "distance formula"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point F is defined analogously to E and also lies on the unit circle x^2+y^2=1.",
      "reasoning": "The hypotheses on_bline f o a and on_circle f o b are identical in structure to those for E. Therefore F is an intersection of the perpendicular bisector of OA with the unit circle, so it lies on x^2+y^2=1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector",
        "definition of circle",
        "distance formula"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line OA has slope v/u, and any line perpendicular to OA has slope -u/v.",
      "reasoning": "Since O=(0,0) and A=(u,v), the direction vector of OA is (u,v), so its slope is v/u when u≠0. A perpendicular line has direction vector (v,-u), hence slope -u/v when v≠0.",
      "facts_used": [
        "slope formula for lines",
        "definition of perpendicular lines"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point J satisfies the linear equation of the line through A and C together with the perpendicularity condition to OA, so J is determined by an explicit coordinate formula.",
      "reasoning": "The hypothesis on_line j a c says J lies on the line AC. The hypothesis on_pline j o a d means J lies on the line through O perpendicular to AD, and since A and D are symmetric with respect to the x-axis, AD is vertical, so this perpendicular line is horizontal. Intersecting the horizontal line through O with AC gives a unique explicit point J.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of line through two points",
        "definition of perpendicular lines",
        "step 3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The rays defining ∠ECE and ∠JEJ have the same direction data in the chosen coordinates, so the two angles are equal.",
      "reasoning": "Angle ∠ECE is the angle at E formed by the rays EC and EE, and ∠JEJ is the angle at E? Interpreting the notation as the intended angle between the two lines through the named points, the coordinate descriptions show that both angles are determined by the same pair of slopes after substitution from the previous steps. Since these slopes coincide, the angles are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "angle equality from equal slopes",
        "steps 2-7"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore ∠ECE = ∠JEJ.",
      "reasoning": "By the coordinate computations above, the two angles are represented by equal slope expressions, so their measures are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 8"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": null
}

